  <h1>mRNA</h1>

  <h2>What is mRNA?</h2>
  <p>Messenger RNA (mRNA) is a type of RNA that carries genetic instructions from DNA to ribosomes, where proteins are made. It acts as a temporary copy of a gene, allowing the cell to use genetic information without exposing the original DNA to damage.</p>
  <p>mRNA is an essential part of gene expression because it serves as the link between DNA and protein synthesis.</p>

  <h2>Structure</h2>
  <p>mRNA is a single-stranded molecule made of nucleotides. Each nucleotide contains:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>A phosphate group</li>
    <li>A ribose sugar</li>
    <li>A nitrogenous base</li>
  </ul>
  <p>The four bases found in mRNA are:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Adenine (A)</li>
    <li>Uracil (U)</li>
    <li>Cytosine (C)</li>
    <li>Guanine (G)</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Unlike DNA, mRNA contains Uracil (U) instead of Thymine (T). The sequence of bases in mRNA carries genetic instructions that will be translated into proteins.</p>

  <h2>How It Works</h2>
  <p>mRNA is produced through a process called transcription. During transcription:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>A gene in DNA is selected.</li>
    <li>The DNA sequence is copied into mRNA.</li>
    <li>The mRNA leaves the nucleus.</li>
    <li>The mRNA travels to a ribosome.</li>
    <li>The ribosome reads the mRNA codons and builds a protein.</li>
  </ol>
  <pre>
DNA
↓
Transcription
↓
mRNA
↓
Ribosome
↓
Protein
  </pre>
  <p>This allows the information stored in DNA to be used for protein production.</p>

  <h2>Functions</h2>
  <p>mRNA performs several important functions:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Carries genetic information from DNA</li>
    <li>Serves as a template for protein synthesis</li>
    <li>Allows genes to be expressed</li>
    <li>Helps regulate cellular activities</li>
    <li>Connects DNA to ribosomes</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Without mRNA, cells would not be able to produce proteins from genetic instructions.</p>

  <h2>Role in Genetics and Biology</h2>
  <p>mRNA plays a central role in the flow of genetic information. According to the Central Dogma of Molecular Biology:</p>
  <pre>
DNA
↓
RNA
↓
Protein
  </pre>
  <p>mRNA is the intermediate molecule that transfers information from genes to the protein-making machinery of the cell. Because proteins perform most cellular functions, mRNA is essential for growth, development, metabolism, and reproduction.</p>

  <h2>Human Relevance</h2>
  <p>Scientists study mRNA to better understand:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Gene expression</li>
    <li>Genetic diseases</li>
    <li>Protein synthesis</li>
    <li>Biotechnology</li>
    <li>Medical treatments</li>
  </ul>
  <p>mRNA technology has become especially important in medicine because it can be used to instruct cells to produce specific proteins.</p>

  <h2>mRNA Vaccines</h2>
  <p>Some modern vaccines use mRNA technology. These vaccines contain mRNA instructions that tell cells to temporarily produce a harmless protein from a pathogen. The immune system learns to recognize the protein and prepares to defend the body if the real pathogen is encountered later. mRNA itself does not change a person's DNA.</p>

  <h2>Interesting Facts</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>mRNA is produced during transcription.</li>
    <li>mRNA is usually much shorter-lived than DNA.</li>
    <li>mRNA carries information from the nucleus to ribosomes.</li>
    <li>The sequence of mRNA codons determines the amino acid sequence of a protein.</li>
    <li>mRNA contains Uracil instead of Thymine.</li>
    <li>mRNA vaccines helped demonstrate the medical potential of mRNA technology.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Key Takeaway</h2>
  <p>mRNA (messenger RNA) is the molecule that carries genetic instructions from DNA to ribosomes. By serving as a temporary copy of a gene, mRNA allows cells to produce proteins and plays a critical role in gene expression and cellular function.</p>

